{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01A8mn38CaXjVQK9Ye2spf1u","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→#' @title Assert that inputs are correct for binary forecast\n     2→#' @description\n     3→#' Function assesses whether the inputs correspond to the\n     4→#' requirements for scoring binary forecasts.\n     5→#' @param observed Input to be checked. Should be a factor of length n with\n     6→#'   exactly two levels, holding the observed values.\n     7→#'   The highest factor level is assumed to be the reference level. This means\n     8→#'   that `predicted` represents the probability that the observed value is\n     9→#'   equal to the highest factor level.\n    10→#' @param predicted Input to be checked. `predicted` should be a vector of\n    11→#'   length n, holding probabilities. Alternatively, `predicted` can be a matrix\n    12→#'   of size n x 1. Values represent the probability that\n    13→#'   the corresponding value in `observed` will be equal to the highest\n    14→#'   available factor level.\n    15→#' @importFrom checkmate assert assert_factor\n    16→#' @inherit document_assert_functions return\n    17→#' @keywords internal_input_check\n    18→assert_input_binary <- function(observed, predicted) {\n    19→  assert_factor(observed, n.levels = 2, min.len = 1)\n    20→  assert_numeric(predicted, lower = 0, upper = 1)\n    21→  assert_dims_ok_point(observed, predicted)\n    22→  return(invisible(NULL))\n    23→}\n    24→\n    25→\n    26→#' @title Check that inputs are correct for binary forecast\n    27→#' @inherit assert_input_binary params description\n    28→#' @inherit document_check_functions return\n    29→#' @keywords internal_input_check\n    30→check_input_binary <- function(observed, predicted) {\n    31→  result <- check_try(assert_input_binary(observed, predicted))\n    32→  return(result)\n    33→}\n    34→\n    35→\n    36→#' Metrics for binary outcomes\n    37→#'\n    38→#' @details\n    39→#'\n    40→#' The functions require users to provide observed values as a factor in order\n    41→#' to distinguish its input from the input format required for scoring point\n    42→#' forecasts. Internally, however, factors will be converted to numeric values.\n    43→#' A factor `observed = factor(c(0, 1, 1, 0, 1)` with two levels (`0` and `1`)\n    44→#' would internally be coerced to a numeric vector (in this case this would\n    45→#' result in the numeric vector `c(1, 2, 2, 1, 1)`). After subtracting 1, the\n    46→#' resulting vector (`c(0, 1, 1, 0)` in this case) is used for internal\n    47→#' calculations. All predictions are assumed represent the probability that the\n    48→#' outcome is equal of the last/highest factor level (in this case that the\n    49→#' outcome is equal to 1).\n    50→#'\n    51→#' You could alternatively also provide a vector like\n    52→#' `observed = factor(c(\"a\", \"b\", \"b\", \"a\"))` (with two levels, `a` and `b`),\n    53→#' which would result in exactly the same internal representation. Probabilities\n    54→#' then represent the probability that the outcome is equal to \"b\".\n    55→#' If you want your predictions to be probabilities that the outcome is \"a\",\n    56→#' then you could of course make `observed` a factor with levels swapped, i.e.\n    57→#' `observed = factor(c(\"a\", \"b\", \"b\", \"a\"), levels = c(\"b\", \"a\"))`\n    58→#'\n    59→#' @param observed A factor of length n with exactly two levels, holding\n    60→#'   the observed values.\n    61→#'   The highest factor level is assumed to be the reference level. This means\n    62→#'   that `predicted` represents the probability that the observed value is\n    63→#'   equal to the highest factor level.\n    64→#' @param predicted A numeric vector of length n, holding probabilities.\n    65→#'   Values represent the probability that the corresponding outcome is equal to\n    66→#'   the highest level of the factor `observed`.\n    67→#' @examples\n    68→#' observed <- factor(sample(c(0, 1), size = 30, replace = TRUE))\n    69→#' predicted <- runif(n = 30, min = 0, max = 1)\n    70→#'\n    71→#' brier_score(observed, predicted)\n    72→#' logs_binary(observed, predicted)\n    73→#' @inheritSection illustration-input-metric-binary-point Input format\n    74→#' @name scoring-functions-binary\n    75→NULL\n    76→\n    77→\n    78→#' @description\n    79→#' **Brier score**\n    80→#'\n    81→#' The Brier Score is the mean squared error between the probabilistic\n    82→#' prediction and the observed outcome. The Brier score is a proper scoring\n    83→#' rule. Small values are better (best is 0, the worst is 1).\n    84→#'\n    85→#' \\deqn{\n    86→#'   \\textrm{Brier\\_Score} = (\\textrm{prediction} - \\textrm{outcome})^2,\n    87→#' }{\n    88→#'   Brier_Score = (prediction - outcome)²,\n    89→#' } where \\eqn{\\textrm{outcome} \\in \\{0, 1\\}}{outcome in {0, 1}}, and\n    90→#' \\eqn{\\textrm{prediction} \\in [0, 1]}{prediction in [0, 1]} represents\n    91→#' the probability that the outcome is equal to 1.\n    92→#' @returns A numeric vector of size n with the Brier scores\n    93→#' @keywords metric\n    94→#' @export\n    95→#' @rdname scoring-functions-binary\n    96→brier_score <- function(observed, predicted) {\n    97→  assert_input_binary(observed, predicted)\n    98→\n    99→  observed <- as.numeric(observed) - 1\n   100→  brierscore <- (observed - predicted)^2\n   101→  return(brierscore)\n   102→}\n   103→\n   104→\n   105→#' Log score for binary outcomes\n   106→#'\n   107→#' @description\n   108→#' **Log score for binary outcomes**\n   109→#'\n   110→#' The Log Score is the negative logarithm of the probability\n   111→#' assigned to the observed value. It is a proper scoring rule. Small values\n   112→#' are better (best is zero, worst is infinity).\n   113→#'\n   114→#' @returns A numeric vector of size n with log scores\n   115→#' @importFrom methods hasArg\n   116→#' @export\n   117→#' @keywords metric\n   118→#' @family log score functions\n   119→#' @rdname scoring-functions-binary\n   120→logs_binary <- function(observed, predicted) {\n   121→  assert_input_binary(observed, predicted)\n   122→  observed <- as.numeric(observed) - 1\n   123→  logs <- -log(1 - abs(observed - predicted))\n   124→  return(logs)\n   125→}\n   126→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01At9ss5uEU3jgBq14SwKQkw","session_id":"8e8f5457-0521-488c-ae9d-60ad5e963fe0","uuid":"28ef5758-9d5a-48b1-9da5-c88b11f610cf"}
