{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01JeTkFDDLiqeWvAbxk6CNmJ","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→#' @title Assert that inputs are correct for quantile-based forecast\n     2→#' @description\n     3→#' Function assesses whether the inputs correspond to the\n     4→#' requirements for scoring quantile-based forecasts.\n     5→#' @param predicted Input to be checked. Should be nxN matrix of predictive\n     6→#'   quantiles, n (number of rows) being the number of data points and N\n     7→#'   (number of columns) the number of quantiles per forecast.\n     8→#'   If `observed` is just a single number, then predicted can just be a\n     9→#'   vector of size N.\n    10→#' @param quantile_level Input to be checked. Should be a vector of size N that\n    11→#'   denotes the quantile levels corresponding to the columns of the prediction\n    12→#'   matrix.\n    13→#' @param unique_quantile_levels Whether the quantile levels are required to be\n    14→#'   unique (`TRUE`, the default) or not (`FALSE`).\n    15→#' @importFrom checkmate assert assert_numeric check_matrix check_vector\n    16→#' @inherit document_assert_functions params return\n    17→#' @keywords internal_input_check\n    18→assert_input_quantile <- function(observed, predicted, quantile_level,\n    19→                                  unique_quantile_levels = TRUE) {\n    20→  assert_numeric(observed, min.len = 1)\n    21→  n_obs <- length(observed)\n    22→\n    23→  assert_numeric(\n    24→    quantile_level, min.len = 1, lower = 0, upper = 1,\n    25→    unique = unique_quantile_levels\n    26→  )\n    27→  n_quantiles <- length(quantile_level)\n    28→  if (n_obs == 1) {\n    29→    assert(\n    30→      # allow one of two options\n    31→      check_numeric_vector(predicted, min.len = n_quantiles),\n    32→      check_matrix(predicted, mode = \"numeric\",\n    33→                   nrows = n_obs, ncols = n_quantiles)\n    34→    )\n    35→    assert(check_vector(quantile_level, len = length(predicted)))\n    36→  } else {\n    37→    assert(\n    38→      check_matrix(predicted, mode = \"numeric\",\n    39→                   nrows = n_obs, ncols = n_quantiles)\n    40→    )\n    41→  }\n    42→  return(invisible(NULL))\n    43→}\n    44→\n    45→#' @title Check that inputs are correct for quantile-based forecast\n    46→#' @inherit assert_input_quantile params description\n    47→#' @inherit check_input_sample return description\n    48→#' @keywords internal_input_check\n    49→check_input_quantile <- function(observed, predicted, quantile_level) {\n    50→  result <- check_try(\n    51→    assert_input_quantile(observed, predicted, quantile_level)\n    52→  )\n    53→  return(result)\n    54→}\n    55→\n    56→\n    57→#' Weighted interval score (WIS)\n    58→#' @description\n    59→#' The WIS is a proper scoring rule used to evaluate forecasts in an interval- /\n    60→#' quantile-based format. See Bracher et al. (2021). Smaller values are better.\n    61→#'\n    62→#' As the name suggest the score assumes that a forecast comes in the form of\n    63→#' one or multiple central prediction intervals. A prediction interval is\n    64→#' characterised by a lower and an upper bound formed by a pair of predictive\n    65→#' quantiles. For example, a 50% central prediction interval is formed by the\n    66→#' 0.25 and 0.75 quantiles of the predictive distribution.\n    67→#'\n    68→#' **Interval score**\n    69→#'\n    70→#' The interval score (IS) is the sum of three components:\n    71→#' overprediction, underprediction and dispersion. For a single prediction\n    72→#' interval only one of the components is non-zero. If for a single prediction\n    73→#' interval the observed value is below the lower bound, then the interval\n    74→#' score is equal to the absolute difference between the lower bound and the\n    75→#' observed value (\"underprediction\"). \"Overprediction\" is defined analogously.\n    76→#' If the observed value falls within the bounds of the prediction interval,\n    77→#' then the interval score is equal to the width of the prediction interval,\n    78→#' i.e. the difference between the upper and lower bound. For a single interval,\n    79→#' we therefore have:\n    80→#'\n    81→#' \\deqn{\n    82→#' \\textrm{IS} = (\\textrm{upper} - \\textrm{lower}) + \\frac{2}{\\alpha}(\\textrm{lower}\n    83→#'  - \\textrm{observed}) *\n    84→#' \\mathbf{1}(\\textrm{observed} < \\textrm{lower}) +\n    85→#' \\frac{2}{\\alpha}(\\textrm{observed} - \\textrm{upper}) *\n    86→#' \\mathbf{1}(\\textrm{observed} > \\textrm{upper})\n    87→#' }{\n    88→#' score = (upper - lower) + 2/alpha * (lower - observed) *\n    89→#' 1(observed < lower) + 2/alpha * (observed - upper) *\n    90→#' 1(observed > upper)\n    91→#' }\n    92→#' where \\eqn{\\mathbf{1}()}{1()} is the indicator function and\n    93→#' indicates how much is outside the prediction interval.\n    94→#' \\eqn{\\alpha}{alpha} is the decimal value that indicates how much is outside\n    95→#' the prediction interval. For a 90% prediction interval, for example,\n    96→#' \\eqn{\\alpha}{alpha} is equal to 0.1. No specific distribution is assumed,\n    97→#' but the interval formed by the quantiles has to be symmetric around the\n    98→#' median (i.e you can't use the 0.1 quantile as the lower bound and the 0.7\n    99→#' quantile as the upper bound).\n   100→#' Non-symmetric quantiles can be scored using the function [quantile_score()]."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01At9ss5uEU3jgBq14SwKQkw","session_id":"8e8f5457-0521-488c-ae9d-60ad5e963fe0","uuid":"f73987a6-aebc-42ab-82cb-7084c2ab6ba2"}
