, predicted)`\n  - After reshaping: `observed` is a vector, `predicted` is a matrix\n  - Called as: `metric_func(observed, predicted, ...)`\n\n- For `score.forecast_quantile()` (line 156-159): `apply_metrics(df, metrics, observed, predicted, quantile_level)`\n  - Passes **three unnamed arguments**\n  - Metrics receive: `metric_func(observed, predicted, quantile_level, ...)`\n\n**Key Implication for Adapters:** Adapters wrap metric functions and must maintain this signature pattern—they receive the data as unnamed positional arguments and must handle them correctly.\n\n---\n\n### 2. **How `get_metrics()` Works - S3 Methods**\n\n**Key File:** `R/metrics.R` (lines 42-66) + class-specific implementations\n\nGeneric function `get_metrics(x, ...)` dispatches to methods based on forecast class:\n\n**Binary Forecasts** (`R/class-forecast-binary.R`, lines 144-150):\n```r\nget_metrics.forecast_binary <- function(x, select = NULL, exclude = NULL, ...) {\n  all <- list(\n    brier_score = brier_score,\n    log_score = logs_binary\n  )\n  select_metrics(all, select, exclude)\n}\n```\n\n**Sample Forecasts** (`R/class-forecast-sample.R`, lines 178-192):\n```r\nget_metrics.forecast_sample <- function(x, select = NULL, exclude = NULL, ...) {\n  all <- list(\n    bias = bias_sample,\n    dss = dss_sample,\n    crps = crps_sample,\n    overprediction = overprediction_sample,\n    underprediction = underprediction_sample,\n    dispersion = dispersion_sample,\n    log_score = logs_sample,\n    mad = mad_sample,\n    ae_median = ae_median_sample,\n    se_mean = se_mean_sample\n  )\n  select_metrics(all, select, exclude)\n}\n```\n\n**Point Forecasts** (`R/class-forecast-point.R`, lines 146-153):\n```r\nget_metrics.forecast_point <- function(x, select = NULL, exclude = NULL, ...) {\n  all <- list(\n    ae_point = Metrics::ae,\n    se_point = Metrics::se,\n    ape = Metrics::ape\n  )\n  select_metrics(all, select, exclude)\n}\n```\n\n**Quantile Forecasts** (`R/class-forecast-quantile.R`, lines 200-214):\n```r\nget_metrics.forecast_quantile <- function(x, select = NULL, exclude = NULL, ...) {\n  all <- list(\n    wis = wis,\n    overprediction = overprediction_quantile,\n    underprediction = underprediction_quantile,\n    dispersion = dispersion_quantile,\n    bias = bias_quantile,\n    interval_coverage_50 = interval_coverage,\n    interval_coverage_90 = purrr::partial(\n      interval_coverage, interval_range = 90\n    ),\n    ae_median = ae_median_quantile\n  )\n  select_metrics(all, select, exclude)\n}\n```\n\n**Key Pattern:**\n- `get_metrics()` returns a **named list of function references** (not calls)\n- Names become column names in the output\n- Functions can be modified via `purrr::partial()` before being included in the list\n\n---\n\n### 3. **How `purrr::partial()` Is Used - The Customization Pattern**\n\n**Documentation:** Mentioned in `R/score.R` (lines 30-51)\n\n**Real Examples from Code:**\n\nFrom `R/class-forecast-quantile.R` (line 208-209):\n```r\ninterval_coverage_90 = purrr::partial(\n  interval_coverage, interval_range = 90\n)\n```\n\nFrom test file `test-metrics-quantile.R` (line 129):\n```r\nmetrics$wis <- purrr::partial(metrics$wis, count_median_twice = TRUE)\n```\n\nFrom test file `test-metrics-quantile.R` (line 175):\n```r\nmetrics$wis <- purrr::partial(metrics$wis, count_median_twice = TRUE)\n```\n\n**How It Works** (from `test-metrics.R`, lines 89-122):\n```r\ntest_that(\"customising metrics via purrr::partial works correctly\", {\n  # Create a customised metric function\n  custom_metric <- purrr::partial(mean, na.rm = TRUE)\n  \n  # Use the customised metric function\n  values <- c(1, 2, NA, 4, 5)\n  expect_equal(custom_metric(values), 3)\n  \n  # Test with unquoting (!!):\n  argument <- c(\"hi\", \"hello\", \"I'm here\")\n  custom_metric <- purrr::partial(print, x = !!argument)\n  expect_output(custom_metric(), \"I'm here\")\n  \n  # Unquoted arguments persist even if original is deleted\n  argument <- NULL\n  expect_output(custom_metric(), \"I'm here\")\n})\n```\n\n**Key Points:**\n- `purrr::partial()` creates a new function with some arguments pre-filled\n- Use `!!` to unquote and evaluate arguments **when the partial is created**, not when it's called\n- This prevents issues with late evaluation and variable scoping\n- The resulting object is still a function (class: `\"function\"`)\n\n---\n\n### 4. **Test Patterns - Fixtures and Helpers**\n\n**Setup File** (`tests/testthat/setup.R`):\n```r\ndata.table::setDTthreads(2) # restricts number of cores used on CRAN\n\n# Pre-computed scores used in tests\nscores_quantile <- score(example_quantile)\nscores_sample_continuous <- score(example_sample_continuous)\nscores_sample_discrete <- score(example_sample_discrete)\nscores_point <- score(example_point)\nscores_binary <- score(example_binary)\nscores_nominal <- score(example_nominal)\n```\n\n**Example Test Data** (from `test-metrics-binary.R`, lines 1-8):\n```r\nobserved <- factor(rbinom(10, size = 1, prob = 0.5))\npredicted <- c(0.425, 0.55, 0.541, 0.52, 0.13, 0.469, 0.86, 0.22, 0.74, 0.9)\ndf <- data.table(\n  observed = observed,\n  predicted = predicted,\n  model = \"m1\",\n  id = 1:10\n)\n```\n\n**Binary Metric Test Pattern** (from `test-metrics-binary.R`, lines 152-163):\n```r\ntest_that(\"Binary metrics work within and outside of `score()`\", {\n  result <- score(as_forecast_binary(df))\n  expect_equal(\n    brier_score(observed, predicted),\n    result$brier_score\n  )\n  \n  expect_equal(\n    logs_binary(observed, predicted),\n    result$log_score\n  )\n})\n```\n\n**Custom Metric with `purrr::partial()` Test Pattern** (from `test-metrics-quantile.R`, lines 116-133):\n```r\ntest_that(\"`wis()` works within score for median forecast\", {\n  test_data <- data.frame(\n    observed = c(1, -15, 22),\n    predicted = 1:3,\n    quantile_level = rep(0.5, each = 3),\n    model = \"model1\",\n    date = 1:3,\n    stringsAsFactors = FALSE\n  ) |>\n    as_forecast_quantile()\n  \n  metrics <- get_metrics(example_quantile) |>\n    select_metrics(select = c(\"ae_median\", \"wis\"))\n  metrics$wis <- purrr::partial(metrics$wis, count_median_twice = TRUE)\n  \n  eval <- score(test_data, metrics = metrics)\n  expect_equal(eval$ae_median, eval$wis)\n})\n```\n\n**Input Validation Test Pattern** (from `test-metrics-binary.R`, lines 37-106):\n```r\ntest_that(\"function throws an error for wrong input formats\", {\n  # observed value not as expected\n  expect_error(\n    assert_input_binary(observed = rnorm(10), predicted = predicted),\n    \"Assertion on 'observed' failed: Must be of type 'factor', not 'double'.\"\n  )\n  \n  # observed value has not 2 levels\n  expect_error(\n    assert_input_binary(factor(1:10), predicted),\n    \"Assertion on 'observed' failed: Must have exactly 2 levels.\"\n  )\n  \n  # wrong length\n  expect_error(\n    assert_input_binary(observed = observed, predicted = runif(15, min = 0, max = 1)),\n    \"`observed` and `predicted` must either be of length 1 or of equal length.\",\n    fixed = TRUE\n  )\n})\n```\n\n---\n\n### 5. **Binary Forecast Specifics**\n\n**Format Definition** (`R/class-forecast-binary.R`, lines 4-14):\n```\n- observed: factor with exactly two levels\n  (highest level is the reference level)\n- predicted: numeric with probabilities\n  (represents P(observed = highest_level))\n```\n\n**Input Validation** (`R/metrics-binary.R`, lines 18-23):\n```r\nassert_input_binary <- function(observed, predicted) {\n  assert_factor(observed, n.levels = 2, min.len = 1)\n  assert_numeric(predicted, lower = 0, upper = 1)\n  assert_dims_ok_point(observed, predicted)\n  return(invisible(NULL))\n}\n```\n\n**Metric Calling** (`R/class-forecast-binary.R`, line 113):\n```r\nscores <- apply_metrics(\n  forecast, metrics,\n  forecast$observed, forecast$predicted\n)\n```\n\n**Available Metrics** (`R/class-forecast-binary.R`, lines 145-149):\n- `brier_score` — measures squared error between prediction and binary outcome\n- `log_score` — logs